<CaseStudy
  title="SecureQuery AI — Secure RAG with RBAC"
  description="A production-hardened RAG system with defence-in-depth role-based access control — Finance, HR, and C-level tiers each see only their authorised documents. PII masking, JWT authentication, guardrails, and cost tracking baked in. 185 tests in ~2 seconds."
  role="AI Systems Engineer · Security"
  period="2025"
  stack={['FastAPI', 'Qdrant', 'Azure OpenAI', 'Streamlit', 'JWT', 'Presidio (PII)', 'Docker']}
  outcome="185 tests passing in ~2s · Finance/HR/C-level RBAC · PII masking on all retrieved content · Full cost tracking per query"
  codeUrl="https://github.com/Mprtham/securequery-ai"
>

  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>
    Most RAG demos retrieve from a single flat document corpus — anyone asking a question gets access to everything. In any real enterprise context, that's a security problem: a Finance analyst should not be able to retrieve HR compensation data, and neither should have access to the board papers visible only to the C-suite. How do you build a RAG system where access control is enforced at retrieval time, not just at the application layer?
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Perimeter-level auth (checking the user's role before they hit the endpoint) is not enough. If the vector store contains mixed-sensitivity documents, a prompt injection or misconfigured retrieval could return unauthorised content. The access control must live at the retrieval layer itself.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The approach</h2>

  <h3>Role-based retrieval (Qdrant payload filters)</h3>
  <p>
    Documents are ingested into Qdrant with a <code>clearance_level</code> payload field — <span class="tag">finance</span>, <span class="tag">hr</span>, <span class="tag">executive</span>, or combinations. Every retrieval query is automatically filtered by the authenticated user's role: a Finance user's query physically cannot return HR or executive documents, because the Qdrant filter is applied before the nearest-neighbour search. The LLM never sees unauthorised content.
  </p>

  <h3>JWT authentication</h3>
  <p>
    Users authenticate via JWT tokens with role claims embedded. The FastAPI middleware validates the token and extracts the role on every request — no session state, stateless by design. Tokens are short-lived (15 minutes) with refresh token rotation.
  </p>

  <h3>PII masking (Microsoft Presidio)</h3>
  <p>
    Retrieved document chunks pass through a Presidio analyser before being included in the LLM context. Names, email addresses, phone numbers, NI numbers, and bank account patterns are masked with entity-type placeholders — <code>[PERSON]</code>, <code>[EMAIL]</code> — before the LLM sees them. The original content is never in the prompt.
  </p>

  <h3>Guardrails + cost tracking</h3>
  <p>
    Input and output guardrails check for prompt injection attempts, off-topic queries, and policy violations. Every query logs token counts and estimated cost (input tokens + output tokens × Azure OpenAI pricing) to a SQLite store — surfaced in a Streamlit admin dashboard so you can see cost per role, per query type, and per document corpus.
  </p>

