  <h2>What broke / what I'd change</h2>
  <p>
    <strong>Presidio false positives on domain-specific terminology.</strong> Financial instrument names and internal product codes triggered PII detection. The fix was a custom allowlist of known non-PII entities — straightforward once identified, but it required careful review of masked output across a diverse document set.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>The 185 tests run fast because of fixture isolation.</strong> Every test that touches Qdrant uses a dedicated test collection, spun up and torn down per test. This was non-trivial to set up but made the suite genuinely reliable — no test leaks state to another. The ~2s runtime is a result of this discipline, not in spite of it.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Production consideration — encryption at rest.</strong> Qdrant supports encrypted collections but it adds operational complexity. In a real deployment, document clearance levels should be combined with encrypted storage and audit logging of every retrieval — who queried what, when. The cost tracking layer in this build is the foundation for that audit trail.
  </p>

